🔹 Problem

Given an array nums, return true if any value appears at least twice, otherwise false.

🧠 1. Brute Force Approach
💡 Idea:

Compare every element with every other element.

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)

bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
    int n = nums.size();
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for(int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if(nums[i] == nums[j]) {
                return true;
            }
        }
    }
    return false;
}
📌 When to use:
Very small input size (n < 1000)
When no extra space is allowed
As a starting point in interviews

⚡ 2. Better Approach (Sorting)
💡 Idea:

Sort the array → duplicates will be adjacent.

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(1) (if in-place sort)
✅ Code:
bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
    sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
    
    for(int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++) {
        if(nums[i] == nums[i - 1]) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
}
📌 When to use:
When modifying array is allowed
Memory is constrained
Better than brute but not optimal

🚀 3. Optimal Approach (Hash Set)
💡 Idea:

Use a set / unordered_set to track seen elements.

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n) (average)
Space: O(n)
✅ Code:
bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
    unordered_set<int> seen;
    
    for(int num : nums) {
        if(seen.count(num)) {
            return true;
        }
        seen.insert(num);
    }
    return false;
}
📌 When to use:
Best choice in most interviews
When extra space is allowed
Need fastest solution
